observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the OIC Municipal Treasurer to enforce existing rules and regulations on the daily remittance and reporting of collections and accountable forms, such as to:
a. require all concerned Collecting Officers to (i) remit all collections intact and regularly at the close of each business day, pursuant to the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume I; (ii) prepare their respective RAAFs following the prescribed format provided in Annex 42 of the NGAS Manual at the end of each month, and submit to the Municipal Treasurer for consolidation; and (iii) accomplish RCDs completely and accurately, ensuring the following:
• indication of Report Numbers;
• completion of details on beginning balance, receipts, issuances, and ending balance of accountable forms; and
• attachment of corresponding JEVs to each RCD submission;
b. prepare the Consolidated RAAF and submit the same together with the individual RAAFs to the Audit Team within the prescribed period.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. review and analyze the reconciling items of reciprocal accounts and take up the necessary adjustments in the respective books of accounts;
b. prepare a reconciliation report of reciprocal accounts to ensure that all reconciling items are resolved and/or adjusted and preform constant review and appraisal of transactions to deter errors and omissions;
c. provide an allowance for impairment on receivable accounts based on analysis of collection rating;
d. prepare the necessary documentation for the filing of request for authority to write-off dormant and long outstanding receivable accounts, for approval of the Municipal Mayor, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005; and
e. submit to the Audit Team the Journal Entry Vouchers pertaining to the adjustments made, including all relevant supporting documents to allow proper verification of the basis for the adjustments.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. identify the officials responsible for the delayed payments and enforce appropriate administrative sanctions;
b. strengthen internal controls over utility payments to prevent recurrence of the noted deficiency;
c. cease the payment of electric bills for privately owned properties not formally under the Municipality’s name; and
d. cause refund of the total amount of ₱103,003.27, representing ₱70,828.70 in surcharges and ₱32,174.57 in payments made for a privately owned property.

We recommended that the:
a. MDRRM Officer (a) comply with the regular preparation and timely submission of the LDRRMFIP and monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of the LDRRMF with proof of receipt by the Office of the Civil Defense (OCD) and the DILG-LGOO; (b) utilize the fund strictly for disaster risk management activities pursuant to RA 10121 and pertinent rules and regulations. Avoid using the fund for other purposes to ensure that the LDRRMF is readily available for its intended purpose; and (c) review and update annually the LDRRMFIP and incorporate the detailed PPAs to be funded from the prior years’ unutilized QRF and DRRMF-MOOE transferred to the special trust fund;
b. Municipal Accountant ensure all necessary supporting documents attached to claims are complete and properly accomplished;
c. Municipal Budget Officer maintain a separate RAAO for the LDRRMF and submit the same to the Audit Team; and
d. Bids and Awards Committee to strictly enforce compliance with Republic Act No. 9184 and its Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR), particularly on the proper preparation, completion, and documentation of all procurement-related forms and requirements.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

OIC-Municipal Accountant to 

(i) prepare complete schedule, breakdown and retrieve the supporting documents relative to the ₱38,484,480.04 Cash-Local Treasury balance of former OIC-Municipal Treasurers and submit the same to the Audit Team so that proper review of the accounts and appropriate action thereof may be undertaken;

We reiterated our previous recommendation that the:
Municipal Mayor (i) instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all Municipality’s PPE and submit the corresponding RPCPPE. During the actual count, the type, description, serial number, acquisition date, name/designation of employee accountable, location and condition of the property counted shall be indicated in the Inventory Sheet. Serially pre-numbered inventory tags shall also be pasted to the counted item/property for easy identification; and (ii) comply with the guidelines and procedures provided for in COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of the PPE to eventually come up with balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability;
Municipal GSO and the Municipal Accountant (i) retrieve relevant records to maintain and update the required Property Cards and the RPLC and PPELC, respectively, per category of PPE and henceforth maintain the same in accordance with Sections 119 and 120 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I; and (ii) Property Acknowledgment Receipts should be used to document issuance of PPE to end-users to establish custodianship and assign accountability;
Inventory Committee, Municipal GSO and the Municipal Accountant, after completing the actual physical count of PPE, perform reconciliation of the result of the actual physical count of PPE with the corresponding PPE records to establish correctness and validity of the account balances presented in the financial statements; and
The Municipal Accountant prepare the lapsing schedule of all PPE to properly determine the correctness and validity of reported depreciation expenses and carrying value of PPE.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the MDRRMO Designate:

Furnish the Audit Team with the required Annual LDRRMFIP and the Report on the Sources and Utilization of the DRRMF for CY 2019, as required under Section 5.1.2, 5.1.5 and 5.1.6 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2002 and Section 12 (6) & (7) of the Philippine Disaster Risk Reduction Management Act of 2010 or Republic Act (RA) No. 10121;

Coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to facilitate the preparation of Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF;

Strictly observe the deadlines on the submission of these reports with the prescribed format in accordance to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-002; and

Ensure that the LDRRMFIP is based on the approved National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Plan (NDRRMP) 2011-2028, validated and accustomed to the local needs encompassing disaster risk reduction and management such as disaster prevention and mitigation, disaster preparedness, disaster response, and disaster rehabilitation and recovery.

a.	ensure that the funds corresponding to the 20% Development Fund for CY 2018 and prior years are utilized exclusively for the implementation of the identified priority development projects embodied in the Annual Investment Plan (AIP) for CYs 2008-2018; 

b.	ensure that the Local Development Council, Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and the Municipal Engineer regularly monitor the status of project implementation so that necessary interventions may be introduced at the earliest time;

c.	submit a satisfactory explanation on the causes/reasons of the delay or non-implementation of the projects totaling ₱63,099,231.68; and 

d.	ensure the timely implementation of priority development programs/projects/activities funded under the 20% DF for the ensuing years in accordance with the provisions in DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1.

We recommended that the:
a.	Local Chief Executive (i) assess the need to engage in consultancy services; (ii) in case there is really a need for consultants, engage only with experts in their respective fields that will be selected thru proper procurement process; (iii) observe rules and regulations on the hiring of consultants; and (iv) ensure that payment for consultancy services are supported with adequate documentation;
b.	Bids and Awards Committee ensure that proper procurement process is always adhered before engaging consultancy services pursuant to the provisions of RA No. 9184;
c.	OIC-Municipal Accountant submit the complete required documents to support the payment for consultancy services pursuant to JMC No. 2, series of 1979, and COA Circular No. 2012-001; and
d.	OIC-Municipal Treasurer (i) ensure the proper withholding of taxes due to BIR from the payment of consultancy services in accordance with Section 2.57.2(a)(6) of Revenue Regulation no. 2-98; and (ii) require authorization document before releasing payment to person other the payee pursuant to COA Circular No. 85-248.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

a.	MDRRMO to submit (i) the reports and documents that would prove the legality, propriety and validity of the events and activities conducted by the MDRRMO; and (ii) a satisfactory explanation why most of the activities were held at Barangay Mangsee, Balabac;

b.	Bids and Awards Committee and BAC Secretariat to (i) explain why the Abstract of Canvass and the Resolution recommending the use of alternative mode of procurement was not signed by the BAC Chairman and one of the BAC Members; (ii) give satisfactory reason as to how and why the suppliers that have business address located in Puerto Princesa City were chosen to supply meals and snacks for MDRRM activities in Barangay Mangsee; and (iii) always adhere to the guidelines and procedures of Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 in all government procurement of the Municipality;

c. 	OIC–Municipal Accountant to comply with Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 on the proper documentation of disbursements of government funds to establish the legality, validity and propriety of the transactions.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive, as head of the GAD Focal Point System to:

a)	cause the timely preparation, submission, review and approval of GAD Plan and Budget and GAD Accomplishment Report by the proper authorities; 

b)	update the GAD Code, if necessary, in coordination with the Sanggunian and disseminate the same to the public in accordance with the guidelines provided under PCW Memorandum Circular No. 2009-1 dated September 16, 2009; 

c)	establish GAD sex-aggregated data or GAD database to serve as basis in performance-based gender responsive planning; and

d)	adopt the HGDG tool to ensure that all Municipal employees, including planning and finance officers, are effectively capacitated on GAD processes.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that:
1. the OIC - Municipal Treasurer to submit the required transaction documents and reports on collections and disbursements every month to the OIC - Municipal Accountant and to strictly observe the policy guidelines on collections and disbursement of government funds such as follows:
a. All payments must be made by checks as prescribed under the principle of imprest system. But when certain conditions required in COA Circular No. 97-002 are met, cash payments may be allowed provided it shall be made by a duly designated Disbursing Officer through his cash advance.
b. Claims must be supported with Payroll/Disbursement Vouchers (DV), Obligation Request (ObR) duly signed by the Municipal Budget Officer and other required documents prior to the release of payment.
c. Collections shall be deposited intact with the authorized depository bank daily or not later than the next banking day.
2. the Municipal Budget Officer to maintain the required RAAOs and verify the balances of appropriations in the RAAOs before certifying as to the existence of available appropriation in the Obligation Requests (ObR). Likewise, he should prepare and submit to the Auditor and the Sangguniang Bayan the Status of Appropriations, Allotments, Appropriations and Balances (SAAOB) not later than the twentieth day after the end of each month;
3. employ cost-cutting measures particularly on local travels which are not urgent, hiring of pump boat or shuttle van, granting of financial assistance or donations in kind, procurement of fuel, office supplies and food supplies/meals/snacks, and hiring of consultants and contractual/job order employees charged to various accounts of Repairs & Maintenance and Other Maintenance & Operating Expenses;
4. devise and implement revenue-enhancing strategies such as aggressive collections of local taxes to help compensate or offset the deficit;
5. recover from the former Municipal Treasurer, Larry I. Eugenio the disbursement vouchers and supporting documents corresponding to his cash accountability of ₱34,835,676.00 and collect any unused cash thereof; and
6. ensure that the 20% Development Fund, DRRMF and Trust Fund shall be utilized exclusively in fulfillment of their respective purposes.

We recommended that the: a. Bids and Awards Committee to (i) prepare and submit Annual Procurement Plan for goods, services and infrastructure projects other than for Common-Use Supplies and Equipment in accordance with 7.1 of RIRR of RA 9184; (ii) exert more diligence in the preparation of APP to ensure the accuracy and completeness of procurement needs based on approved PPMPs and (iii) ensure that the items not available in PS-DBM is well supported by certification from the PS-DBM regarding stocks availability;
b. Municipal Mayor to instruct the BAC and GSO to procure common-use supplies at the PS-DBM as being required by AO 17, DBM Circular Letter No. 2011-6 and IRR of RA 9184.
c. BAC and GSO, in case of non-availability of items in the PS-DBM, the procurement of these common use goods should be procured in bulk quantities to avoid piecemeal purchases and Splitting of Purchase Order.

We recommended that management:
a. Strictly adhere with the provisions set forth under COA Circular No. 77-61 dated September 26, 1977 to properly control the utilization of fuel;
b. Strictly comply with the provisions 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (R-IRR) of Republic Act No. 9184 in all government procurement;
c. Submit to the Auditor the relevant basic documentary requirements lacking in the disbursement vouchers such as Summary of Monthly Reports of Fuel Consumption and Monthly Report of Official Travels and Driver’s Trip Tickets otherwise, said transactions shall be suspended in audit;
d. Strictly comply with the Section 4 of PD No. 1445, and COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 on the documentary requirements in all government transactions;
e. Submit to the Auditor a complete and updated list of serviceable municipal vehicles to ascertain the reliability of fuel consumption and for validation purposes.

We recommended that the: a. BAC and OIC-Budget Officer to prepare the PPMP and APP and make sure that these PPMPs and APPs were carefully planned and scheduled to better manage the procurement, produce economical result, make the procurement procedures more efficient and practical. Ensure that the APP adheres with guidelines prescribed by Appendix “2” of R-IRR of RA 9184;
b. BAC should exert extra effort in the planning preparation of the procurement to attract number of bidders to join the bidding to promote competitive bidding;
c. Municipal Mayor to instruct the BAC to create a TWG to assist them in the procurement process. Likewise, ensure that the BAC secretariat to properly carry out its functions and responsibilities in accordance to Section 14.1 of RA 9184;
d. BAC to strictly comply to Section 10 of RA 9184 and all the requirements and procedures in the R-IRR of Republic Act No. 9184 to adhere to the principles of transparency, competitiveness, accountability, equity, efficiency, and economy in its procurement process.

We recommended that the: a. OIC – Municipal Accountant and OIC – Municipal Treasurer to (i) strictly comply with the timely rendition of accounts and financial reports so as not to delay the verification and post-audit activities; and (ii) observe the deadline of submission to the Audit Team the required financial reports and documents;
b. OIC – Municipal Budget Officer to prepare and submit the required Status of Appropriations, Allotments, Obligations and Balances (SAAOB) for CY 2017; and;
c. Municipal Mayor to (i) require all accountable officers concerned to submit all the financial documents and for each month for the preparation of the financial reports and (ii) impose sanctions against the accountable officers who continuously failed to abide with the timely submission of financial documents and reports as stipulated in Section 122 of PD No. 1445 and Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code of the Philippines.

We recommended for the Municipality to undertake the following recommendations:

e Municipal officials and employees should immediately stop the hiring of pump boats for special trips unless absolutely necessary in the performance of the assignment. RERs should be properly and completely filled out as to the required information.

e Limit disbursements for expenditures which are absolutely necessary in the hiring of Job Order personnel and repairs and maintenance of the municipal watercrafts, Consider acquiring brand new and fuel efficient motor boats in lieu of excessive repairs and maintenance;

e Prepare and submit Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption, Monthly Report of Official Travels duly supported with duly approved trip tickets;

e All disbursements for pump boat hire, repairs and maintenance and fuel procurement should be supported with complete, original and valid documentations;

e Stop resorting to reimbursement of purchases. Strictly comply with the procurement procedure and requirements prescribed in RA 9184.

Disbursements found to be irregular, unnecessary and excessive shall be disallowed in audit.

We recommended for the Municipal Mayor to: © Require the Municipal Accountant to submit on time the complete financial reports and other documents as required under NGAS Manual for LGUs, COA Circular No. 2010-001 and PPSAS Nos. | and 2. Likewise, the Statement of Changes in Net Assets/Equity and Statement of Comparison of Budget and Actual Amounts (SCBAA) for CY 2015 should be submitted immediately. We further recommend the preparation and inclusion as disclosure in the notes to financial statements the reconciliation of the surplus/deficit from ordinary activities with the net cash flow from operating activities and the utilization of the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund;

Compel the Municipal Budget Officer to submit immediately the SAAOB for the period January 2015 to December 2015. Otherwise, suspension of the payment of salaries of the Municipal Budget Officer is recommended until he has complied with the submission of the required SAAOB; and

Strictly require the Municipal Treasurer to submit monthly the complete transaction documents and reports to the Municipal Accountant for the timely preparation and submission of the financial reports of the latter.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that:
a. Municipal Treasurer to submit the required transaction documents and reports on collections and disbursements every month to the Municipal Accountant and to strictly observe the policy guidelines on collections and disbursement of government funds such as follows:
i. All payments must be made by checks as prescribed under the principle of imprest system. But when certain conditions required in COA Circular No. 97-002 are met, cash payments may be allowed provided it shall be made by a duly designated Disbursing Officer through his cash advance.
ii. Claims must be supported with duly approved Payroll/Disbursement Vouchers (DV), Obligation Request (ObR) duly signed by the Municipal Budget Officer and other required documents prior to the release of payment.
iii. Collections shall be deposited intact with the authorized depository bank daily or not later than the next banking day.
b. the Municipal Budget Officer to maintain the required RAAOs and verify the balances of appropriations in the RAAOs before certifying as to the existence of available appropriation in the Obligation Requests (ObR). Likewise, he should prepare and submit to the Auditor and the Sangguniang Bayan the Status of Appropriations, Allotments, Appropriations and Balances (SAAOB) not later than the twentieth day after the end of each month;
c. employ cost-cutting measures particularly on local travels which are not urgent, hiring of pump boat or shuttle van, granting of financial assistance or donations in kind, procurement of fuel, office supplies and food supplies/ meals/snacks, and hiring of consultants and contractual/job order employees charged to various accounts of Repairs & Maintenance and Other Maintenance & Operating Expenses;
d. devise and implement revenue-enhancing strategies such as aggressive collections of local taxes to help compensate or offset the deficit;
e. recover from the former Municipal Treasurer, Larry I. Eugenio the disbursement vouchers and supporting documents corresponding to his cash accountability of ₱34,835,676.00 and collect any unused cash thereof; and
f. ensure that the 20% Development Fund, DRRMF and Trust Fund shall be utilized exclusively in fulfillment of their respective purposes.

We recommended that the ICO-Municipal Accountant:
a. Strictly observe the monthly preparation of Bank Reconciliation Statements to determine the correct balance of the Cash in Bank account in the financial statements, in compliance with Section 3 of COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996;
b. Exert diligent effort in reconciling the book and bank balances on a timely basis and submit the Bank Reconciliation Statements and other relevant documents showing that the identified reconciling items were properly recorded and adjusted in the books of accounts;
c. Request from the depository bank the copies of Credit and Debit Memos to determine their validity and effect the necessary adjustments;
d. Communicate with banks for all reconciling items which still need verification; and
e. Reconcile accounting records with the cash book of the ICO-Municipal Treasurer. Henceforth, both offices should reconcile their records regularly so that errors or discrepancies that may be noted could be readily adjusted.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to:
a. Require the former ICO-Municipal Treasurer to produce cashbook and to reconcile with the ICO-Municipal Accountant with their books of accounts and submit to the Office of the Auditor the report of his accountability in accordance to Section 80 of PD 1445;
b. Assign competent personnel to participate in the reconciliation process, exert effort in tracing up origin of those questionable amounts, if any, identify those accountable persons responsible for such deviations and assist in providing pertinent documents to support necessary adjustments in the books to reflect the correct balances of the account in each fund;
c. Require all AOs (ICO-Municipal Treasurer, collectors and disbursing officers) who are handling cash or being granted cash advances to maintain cashbooks and strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; Section 26, Volume II of MNGAS for LGUs; and Section 310 of RA 7160. All AOs should (a) properly maintain their cashbook by fund; (b) regularly update, balance and reconcile records with the cash on hand daily or as necessary; and (c) reconcile the cashbooks with the records of the ICO-Municipal Accountant at least quarterly to ensure that the recorded transactions are complete, reliable, accurate and timely.
